post_text: Orchard Elementary Pre-K teacher Ms. Patterson asked her four-year-olds to think about their favorite color and then pick out the crayon for that color. "Write the first letter of your first name. If you can already write your whole name, then please do that," she said, and then she gave them a few minutes to hold their work up to their webcams so she could see it. Keeping the attention of our youngest students takes energy and creativity, which is what Ms. Patterson and her co-teacher, Ms. Wright have. Between lessons, they encourage students to take nature walks in their yard and sometimes they have show-and-tell. Meanwhile, in the fifth-grade hall, students in a language arts class being co-taught by Ms. Montgomery and Dr. Kigango were making inferences - using evidence from various stories to draw conclusions. #LearningLeadingRemotely

post_text: "'I love pizza.' Is that a compound or simple sentence?" Ms. Williams asked her second-graders at J.E. Turner Elementary. "Are they telling us one thing or two things?" To that, a boy replied correctly: "One thing, so that makes it simple." Across campus, third-grade teacher Ms. Abston used a white board to show her students how to round 278 to the nearest 10. It was a great day for remote learning. #LearningLeadingRemotely

post_text: For Spirit Day, the first-graders in Mrs. Frye's class at North Mobile K-8 brought their teddy bears to their virtual class. They introduced their bears - in one case a stuffed rabbit - and said what they loved most about their fluffy friends. They worked on their short A and O sounds and then they practiced their writing by pondering the question: Would you rather eat apple sauce or a piece of apple pie? It was the start of a great day all over the school, where kindergarten teachers used a document camera to show students how to write uppercase and lowercase letters, and fifth-graders learned about different types of scientists. #LearningLeadingRemotely

post_text: "Suppose you found a box of gold coins under your bed. What would you do?" The third-graders in Ms. Allsup's class at Chastang-Fournier K-8 had a couple of minutes to write their answers to that question. Several shared their replies. "I would buy my sister a house, and my mom a car, and me a big-screen TV," a girl read her answer aloud. "Then I would save the rest for the rest of my years." The Falcons were busy teaching and learning today. #LearningLeadingRemotely

Congratulations, Hankins! #LearningLeading

post_text:
Congratulations to Williamson High math teacher and department chair Lola Boldon, who has been selected as an SEC “Extra Yard For Teachers” recipient. Boldon was nominated by Alabama basketball player Jasmine Walker, who was taught by Boldon during a previous stop in her teaching career at Jeff Davis High in Montgomery.

The "Extra Yard for Teachers" program recognizes K-12 teachers who have made a major impact in the lives of SEC student-athletes. A story on Boldon will be broadcast on SEC Nation or the SEC Network during Saturday coverage during the college football season. In addition, Boldon will be awarded a grant in the amount of $3,500 to be used for the purpose of school supplies and materials through DonorsChoose.org. Congratulations, Ms. Boldon! #LearningLeading

post_text: Reminder: We will serve this week's meals on TUESDAY, not Monday, due to the Labor Day holiday. No lunch number/barcode will be required on Tuesday or throughout our time of remote learning as the federal government has decided not to require us to collect that information. Most schools offer pick-up from 9 a.m. until 1 p.m., but check with your school for specific details.

post_text: Just two more days until school starts! Make sure your student has an organized workspace to help them focus on schoolwork. It should include their laptop or tablet, along with pencils, paper and other supplies. Other helpful items might include a caddy or organizer, a calendar to keep up with assignments, and headphones or earbuds. A tri-fold board like those used for science projects is one idea to create a personalized space that says: It's time to study! #LearningLeadingRemotely

post_text:
Get ready to connect in four days! Mobile County Public Schools has distributed 40,000 laptops and other devices to families and is in the process of delivering more. We are encouraging families to take advantage of free internet vouchers from the Alabama Broadband Connectivity initiative. The state mailed these this week (if you have questions, call 1-888-212-4998 or visit abcstudents.org). We will park 20 buses in communities throughout the county that lack internet connectivity so our students can log on.

If you do not have your device yet, don’t stress. Be patient, and be flexible. You can use the devices you already have at home – your phone, a tablet, a laptop, a desktop – to log on to Schoology until your device comes in. We have experienced shipping delays, and will deliver the rest as soon as we receive them. #LearningLeadingRemotely

post_text: With the first day of school approaching next week, schools across the county introduced students to their teachers for the year. The Mobile County Board of School Commissioners approved this calendar today, and we are looking forward to officially beginning instruction remotely on September 1.

post_text:
A reminder for MCPSS parents to be on the lookout for a letter today from Alabama Broadband Connectivity. Eligible families will get a prepaid voucher number for free internet access!

Alabama Gov. Kay Ivey has committed CARES Act funding to deliver free high-speed internet access to eligible K-12 students in their homes this fall. The letters going out today will include a voucher number needed to get free service through Dec. 30, 2020, and a list of service providers to contact to set it up.

If you qualify, contact one of the listed service providers as soon as you can. The sooner you call, the sooner your student will be ready for a successful remote learning experience.

For further assistance and more information, contact the Alabama Broadband Connectivity for Students program at 1-888-212-4998 or visit abcstudents.org.

post_text:
Incoming freshman Lily Hoyle of Davidson High School is one of 7 MCPSS students & recent graduates who were selected as Mobile Bay Magazine Wonder Kids! The story in its August 2020 issue profiles 11 Mobile-area students "who have exceeded all expectations for anyone their ages. Despite such trying times, these young men and women are the embodiment of excellence."

Hoyle was also Mobile County Public Schools' 2020 middle school Learning Leading Award winner. From the Mobile Bay Magazine story: "Lily embodies the adage that age is just a number. While she was attending Phillips Preparatory School, her documentary, focused on racially inspired lynchings, was screened at the National Museum of African American History and Culture in Washington, D.C. Along with filmmaking, she raises money for a school in Africa by selling painted oysters at a craft fair."

You can see all of our Wonder Kids here and order a copy of the magazine (photo by Matthew Coughlin): https://mobilebaymag.com/wonder-kids/

post_text:
Great news for eligible MCPSS students and parents: Free internet access!

Alabama Gov. Kay Ivey has committed CARES Act funding to deliver free internet access to eligible K-12 students in their homes this fall. Families of eligible students will receive a letter sometime after Aug. 24 that will include a prepaid voucher number and a list of service providers to contact to set up free high-speed internet service through Dec. 30, 2020.

This is perfect timing for our Remote Learning Plan. If your student does not have reliable internet access, be on the lookout for this letter. If you qualify, contact one of the listed service providers as soon as you can; the sooner you call the sooner your student will be ready for a successful remote learning experience.

For further assistance and more information, contact the Alabama Broadband Connectivity for Students program at 1-888-212-4998 or visit abcstudents.org.

post_text: Williamson High School's basketball team received State Championship rings at a socially distanced ceremony. The Lions won the 4A State Championship back in March and had to postpone celebrations due to COVID-19. Coach Shumbe Hunter explained that the 55 stones on the ring represent the 50 regular season games the team won over two seasons and the 5-game run that the Lions had in the playoffs. The number 14 is also on the ring in memory of teammate Tycorey Crawford, who died in 2019. Crawford's parents accepted a ring in his honor. #LearningLeading #TeamMCPSS #IamMCPSS

post_text: BREAKING NEWS. Join us in congratulating Bryant High School's David Dai, who was named Alabama's Alternate Teacher of the Year today. That makes him this year's top-ranked high school teacher in the state. We would also like to congratulate Alabama's new Teacher of the Year, Dr. Andrew Jackson of Eden Elementary School in Pell City. A native of Bayou la Batre, Mr. Dai teaches math at his alma mater. Dai co-sponsors Bryant's scholars' bowl and HiQ teams, the Student Government Association, and Youth Activist Coalition. He taught Algebra I as part of mcpssTV's LIVE Lessons this past spring. He also coaches ultimate frisbee and disc golf after school. We are very proud of you, Mr. Dai. #LearningLeading #IamMCPSS #TeamMCPSS

post_text:
Class of 2020 MCPSS graduate Kelsey White of Baker High School is one of 7 MCPSS students & recent graduates selected as Mobile Bay Magazine Wonder Kids! The story in its August 2020 issue profiles 11 Mobile-area students "who have exceeded all expectations for anyone their ages. Despite such trying times, these young men and women are the embodiment of excellence."

White is a standout hurdler in track and field, and a state champion in the heptathlon, which includes the 100-meter hurdles, 200-meter sprint, 800-meter run, high jump, long jump, shot put and javelin. She is attending Samford University this fall on an athletic scholarship and majoring in psychology, with plans to become a clinical psychologist.

We'll share the rest of the MCPSS students featured in the coming days. Or you can see them all here and order a copy of the magazine (photo by Matthew Coughlin): https://mobilebaymag.com/wonder-kids/

post_text:
Recent MCPSS graduate Vanessa Siggers of Murphy High School is one of 7 MCPSS students & recent graduates featured in Mobile Bay Magazine's "Wonder Kids" feature! The story in its August 2020 issue profiles 11 Mobile-area students "who have exceeded all expectations for anyone their ages. Despite such trying times, these young men and women are the embodiment of excellence."

Siggers was also Mobile County Public Schools' 2020 high school Learning Leading Award winner. She is headed to the University of South Alabama to triple-major in Spanish, French and Biomedical Science and has received early acceptance to USA's medical school.

“Learning about science makes you think," she told the magazine. "It’s weird how so many phenomena occur around us, and there’s not really any direct evidence to explain everything … It’s just kind of mind-blowing.”

We'll share the rest of the MCPSS students featured in the coming days. Or you can see them all here and order a copy of the magazine (photo by Matthew Coughlin): https://mobilebaymag.com/wonder-kids/

post_text:
Despite finishing the 2019-20 school year remotely due to COVID-19, 180 Mobile County Public Schools students earned AP Scholar distinction in 2020, including 28 students named AP Scholars with Honor, 41 named AP Scholars with Distinction, 17 who earned AP Capstone Diplomas and four named National AP Scholars: Baker High School's Zachary Blair, Isabella Martin, Logan Phelps and Sarah Sims. In all, 1,043 MCPSS students took 1,638 AP exams, taking the opportunity to earn college credit while still in high school.

Congratulations to all our AP Scholars, who exemplify our motto of: Learning Today. Leading Tomorrow. #LearningLeading

post_text: Hey, parents! Leadership Mobile will have a local leader read a bedtime story with your kids every night beginning on August 3. Check out the Facebook page below for more information.
shared_text:
Bedtime Stories by Leaders in Mobile
July 31 at 8:07 AM ·

We kick off our bedtime stories Monday night with Brandon Maye! Tune in at 7:00 PM to this Facebook page for your child’s bedtime story. Brandon is a product of MCPSS Davidson High School! He was an All-American linebacker for Clemson Football at Clemson University and also attended Mississippi State University. Brandon Maye is actively involved with the youth in our community through his nonprofit The Brandon Maye Legacy Foundation. He is a real estate investor in our city who believes not only in success, but more importantly in giving back to the community and making a difference in the lives of others! Brandon is a best selling author and motivational speaker. Join us Monday night at 7:00 PM! 📚

post_text: Calendar update: With remote classes starting on September 1, we are working on a new calendar for the 2020-21 school year. We are seeking a waiver from the Alabama Department of Education so that we can end our year near the currently scheduled date of May 27. We are also trying to keep all of our holidays the same as we know families may have made plans based on the calendar we adopted this spring. Once we hear back from the state, we will bring a new calendar up for a vote to be approved by the Mobile County Board of School Commissioners. One change we are proposing is for school to be out on Nov. 3, as 20 of our schools are polling sites on Election Day. As Superintendent Chresal Threadgill announced recently, due to the rising number of coronavirus cases in Mobile County, we are planning to do our first quarter all remotely. We are hoping to be back in school for the second quarter, but we will continue to assess coronavirus numbers before making that determination. Thank you for your continued patience as we work through this pandemic together.

post_text: Students from all 12 of our high schools worked with Chief Lawrence Battiste and officers with the Mobile Police Department today to better the relationship between the police and the community at-large. Through a program called Bridging the Gap, students and officers acted out various scenarios involving the police, such as domestic disturbance calls and traffic stops. The students evaluated how the police and the suspects behaved in each scenario and discussed ways we can all work together to improve our interactions with others. #LearningLeading

post_text: BREAKING NEWS. Join us in congratulating Bryant High School math teacher David Dai. He has just been named one of the Top Four finalists for Alabama Teacher of the Year! A native of Bayou La Batre, Dai co-sponsors Bryant's scholars' bowl and HiQ teams, the Student Government Association, and Youth Activist Coalition. He taught Algebra I as part of mcpssTV's LIVE Lessons this past spring. He also coaches ultimate frisbee and disc golf after school. "I'm humbled and honored to be part of this group of educators who have been named to the Top Four," Dai said. "We are teachers who even through a pandemic are trying to be a light for our students."

post_text:
Congratulations to Jamie Bosarge of Alma Bryant High School and Ramona Savell of Clark-Shaw School of Math, Science & Technology, who have been named as local winners of the Shell Science Lab Regional Challenge. The awards are presented to teachers who demonstrate innovative approaches to teaching science.

Bosarge and Savell were awarded science lab makeover support packages worth $15,000 and $10,000, respectively, which will allow them to purchase new lab equipment, kits and supplies. They'll also receive a one-year membership in the National Science Teaching Association and will be registered to attend the NSTA's STEM Conference, which will be held virtually this year.

"STEM careers are on the rise and students need to be exposed to opportunities to encourage their own investigations and problem solving skills in safe, well-equipped environments," Bosarge said. "I plan to use the funds to provide a hands-on STEM education for my students at Alma Bryant High School."

Congratulations to both these exemplary educators! #TeamMCPSS #LearningLeading

Mobile County Public Schools parents: Tomorrow (July 2), you will be receiving a phone call from MCPSS with a survey that will help us in our planning for the 2020-21 school year. You will be asked about your household’s access to reliable internet, whether your student has a laptop or desktop computer (not a cell phone or tablet), your transportation needs and your instructional preference.

If you have students enrolled in more than one MCPSS school, you will receive one call per student. Please complete the survey in every call. It is imperative that we receive your feedback in order to plan for a safe and productive 2020-21 school year. Thank you for helping us serve your students.

Congratulations to E.R. Dickson and Breitling elementary schools, which are the only schools in Alabama to be named as winners of the 2020 American Student Council Association School of Excellence Award. The award, presented by the National Association of Elementary School Principals, recognizes outstanding achievement by student councils in community service, student leadership, citizenship and school spirit.

Winners were selected based on projects that their student council completed during the 2019-2020 school year, as well as their student council constitution and election procedures. Councils were also required to submit letters of recommendation from their principal and student council president. #TeamMCPSS #LearningLeading

Two Murphy High Class of 2020 graduates were recently honored with lucrative scholarships.

Timothy Lett is the first recipient of the Serena Willcox scholarship. A group of former students established a $5000 scholarship in honor of Willcox, a former assistant principal at Murphy. Lett will attend the University of Alabama this fall and major in political science.

Cadet 1SG Marcus Brown has been awarded a full three-year ROTC scholarship and the Heritage Gold Scholarship at Alabama A&M University starting this fall. Upon successful graduation and completion of all ROTC requirements, he will earn a commission into the U.S. Army as a 2LT.

Congratulations to both iof these graduates! #IamMCPSS #LearningLeading

Mobile County Public Schools was proud to join community leaders and representatives of the Schmidt family today in announcing plans to build The Miracle League of West Mobile: Schmidt Family Park, a baseball field and playground for special needs children. The park will be constructed on Johnson Road, about two miles southwest of the intersection of Airport Boulevard and Snow Road.

Several community organizations have already stepped up to the plate, donating land, providing funds to pave the road and more, including: the Alabama Pecan Development Company, Inc., Schmidt-Barton Family Fund, South Alabama Utilities, MCPSS and the Mobile County Commission.

Donations are now being accepted at mcpss.com/miracleleague to cover the remaining costs associated with the park. Read more: https://www.mcpss.com/sys/content/newspost/867f23716ff7483cafea27a4f0f63645

post_text: Mobile Police Chief Lawrence Battiste IV and officers from the Mobile Police Department met with about 70 students from all of Mobile County’s public schools and several private schools today at Murphy High School. Battiste and the officers spent about four hours with the students. Mobile Mayor Sandy Stimpson stopped by and answered some questions as well. post_text: ICYMI: MCPSS and the Barton Academy Foundation held a ceremony to kick off the interior renovations at the historic Barton Academy on Thursday. post_text: FEEDING OUR CHILDREN:At Morningside Elementary, cafeteria manager Tina Robinson and her team handed out about 600 breakfasts and lunches every day. Joining her were Annicer Bendolph, Ola Mae Crimes, Mary Tims and volunteer Jalen Barley, with workers from several other schools helping out the last few weeks of the program. On Friday, the last day of the program, they served turkey sandwiches, chips, broccoli, carrots, fruit and juice. "I feel real good about helping the community and the children," Robinson said. "I miss them." Thank you to the workers and volunteers at Morningside and all our cafeterias for working so hard to make sure our children are fed! #IamMCPSS

We are ready to host safe ceremonies to honor our Class of 2020. #LearningLeading #TeamMCPSS

post_text: FEEDING OUR CHILDREN: The cafeteria workers and volunteers at Hollinger's Island Elementary School have been giving out about 500 meals a day at the school and on a bus that visits B.C. Rain High, Pillans Middle, and Gilliard and Maryvale elementary schools. HIES cafeteria manager Trish Haywood has been assisted by Shan Henderson, Deborah Wilkerson, Kim Jones, Jessica Wright, Gail Weston and Central Office volunteers Bryan Hack and Denise Riemer. A second crew has been managed by Ella Grant cafeteria manager Erica Dickinson, with help from workers from three other schools. On Thursday, the menu included chicken tenders, broccoli and cheese, potato wedges, eggs and biscuits, fruit, juice and milk. "To be able to make sure they have nutrition to make it throughout this time, it feels good to do so," Dickinson said of the students. "When they see us, their little faces light up." Thank you to everyone who has been feeding our children at Hollinger's Island.

post_text:
Congratulations to Hutchens Elementary parent and PTA President Kyle Young on being the first winner of the National Volly Award, an award established by Booster to recognize the top school volunteer in the country. Mr. Young serves in many roles at Hutchens, volunteering his time to give Accelerated Reader tests, helping in the office or on school field trips, and bringing innovative ideas to the PTA to increase fundraising and parent involvement.

"From the very first time I met you, you were picking up recycling and I thought: 'Oh my gosh, he does that, he drives the bus, he's the PTA President, he can do everything,'" Hutchens teacher Julie Neidhardt said of Mr. Young. "You are so deserving of this award."

We thank Mr. Young and all the other parents and volunteers who give of their time to help make our schools vibrant and engaged learning environments. #IamMCPSS #LearningLeading

On top of owning his own business, Kyle volunteers his time testing the students with the school’s Accelerator Reader and jumping at any opportunity to assist in the office or on school field trips. As PTA President, he works continuously to bring innovative fundraising ideas to Hutchens and increase parent involvement in their students’ lives.

To learn more about the Volly Awards and see all the nominees, visit www.vollyawards.com

post_text: FEEDING OUR CHILDREN: Starting out with a staff of just five, Alba Middle cafeteria manager Teonda Lyons saw the numbers of meals produced at the site rise from 600 to a peak of about 1,700. She has been helped at the site by Kimberly Seaman, Mary Jo Weller, Dana Lee and Ronda Bosarge. Dixon Elementary cafeteria manager Heidi Ladnier and her crew have since joined in to help and the site is still handing out about 1,400 meals a day. On Tuesday, Alba served spaghetti, green beans, fruit cups, cheese quesadillas, juice and milk. The community has shown their appreciation in numerous ways, Lyons said, including signs posted near the cafeteria that read: Heroes Work Here. "It was very hard in the beginning," Lyons said. "When we pulled in in the morning and those signs were posted, it gave us a breath of fresh air." Thank you to all the heroes at Alba Middle for feeding our children! #IamMCPSS

post_text: It's a wrap! Thank you for watching our LIVE Lessons on mcpssTV, Facebook, YouTube, Fox 10.6 and UTV 44. About 150 educators and other professionals were involved in the production of these lessons, which have received praise from the Alabama Department of Education and even national attention. We broadcast 185 hours of instruction taught by master teachers for pre-k through 11th grade. The lessons received a half-million views on social media alone. We enjoyed bringing these lessons to you at home during this pandemic, and we hope you learned many interesting new things. Keep reading and learning, and have a great summer! #LearningLeading

post_text: FEEDING OUR CHILDREN: With a hard-working crew of cafeteria workers and volunteers, the cafeteria at Craighead Elementary School has been serving about 1,200 meals per day at the school and on a bus that delivers to George Hall and Leinkauf elementary schools and Williamson High. Isis Morrison has managed the cafeteria through most of this feeding program, with help on her original crew from Erin Morrison, Angela Sykes, Renee Robinson, Clara Logan and volunteers Robert F. Barrow, Belinda Roberts, D.H. Walton, Denise Johnson, Kistra Scott, Erica Burrell, Tracy Hudson and Joseph Roberson and bus driver Stephanie Taylor. post_text: FEEDING OUR CHILDREN: Cafeteria manager Mary Green has had no shortage of help at LeFlore High School. Her initial crew during this feeding program included Latchia Kitt, Cesar Hollie, Denise Brackett, Latonya Gale, Linda Brown, Dedra Jones, Barbara McCovery, Tracy Brady and Alferdetta Howard. The last couple weeks, the site has been run by a new crew managed by Gloria Jones of Booker T. Washington, Deborah Godfrey of Williamson and Tonya Knowles of Florence Howard, with crew members from LeFlore and four other schools. The site has needed all that help, as it is giving out between 1,100 and 1,500 meals a day. On Friday, they served biscuits and eggs, corn dogs, potato wedges, fruit, juice and milk. "When we first started out, we had no idea how we were going to fill that need," Green said. "It does my heart good to help fulfill that need." Thank you to all the workers and volunteers who have been feeding our students at LeFlore High School! #IamMCPSS

post_text: FEEDING OUR CHILDREN: The cafeteria workers at Augusta Evans provided bagged meals today of deli sandwiches, pudding cups, chips, cheese sticks, cherry pastries, oranges, juice and milk. "A lot of these children only eat at school," Wilmoth said. "We know that we are really making a huge difference in their lives." Thank you to everyone feeding our students from the Augusta Evans cafeteria! #IamMCPSS

post_text: FEEDING OUR CHILDREN: The cafeteria workers and volunteers at Alma Bryant High School have been handing out about 1,100 bagged meals a day, with each bag including breakfast and lunch. Last week was particularly busy, as the site gave out 10,000 meals at the school and on a bus that stops at Dixon and St. Elmo elementary schools and two local churches. On Wednesday, the menu included chicken sandwiches, tater logs, broccoli, cereal, string cheese, juice and milk. Bryant cafeteria manager Toy Hollingshead has been assisted by Heidi Ladnier, Cindy Payne, Diane McMillan and a large group of volunteers, including Lori Zirlott, Robin West, Joshua West, Mary Ann Bartle and many teachers at the school. "I know a lot of people are hurting for food," Hollingshead said, "so I think these meals mean a lot to a lot of people." Thank you to all the workers and volunteers that have kept the Alma Bryant cafeteria running! #IamMCPSS

post_text:
The MCPSS Leadership Academy Cohort I surprised Superintendent Chresal Threadgill, Deputy Superintendent Dr. Lakesha Brackins & Coordinator of Professional Learning, Special Projects, & Innovation Dr. Amanda Jones today with gifts of appreciation.

The Academy is designed to hone the leadership skills of current and emerging MCPSS administrators. "What I want is a legacy of great leaders who are doing it for the right reasons," Threadgill told the cohort.

"I think it's just so essential that professional educators, especially our leaders and visionaries, have an opportunity to have a network like we've been provided with this group," said cohort member Tiffany Buchanan, assistant principal at Blount High School. "We always need inspiration."

They are already leading, but that doesn't mean our administrators stop learning. #IamMCPSS #LearningLeading

post_text: FEEDING OUR CHILDREN: The cafeteria team at Blount High School served 515 bagged meals of breakfast pizza, pulled pork, potato wedges, fruit, juice and milk on Wednesday. Blount cafeteria manager Quandra Carter has been assisted by Racheal Arnold, Lillian McCoy, Juanita Quincy, Faye Napier and Mr. Winston, the bus driver. "It feels good to actually see the kids come around, because all the kids love Ms. Quandra and I miss my kids and I get to see them personally and call them by their name," Carter said. Thank you to all those who are helping feed kids at Blount and our other feeding program sites! #IamMCPSS

post_text: FEEDING OUR CHILDREN: The cafeteria workers and volunteers at Hankins Middle School have been handing out an average of about 1,000 bagged meals a day. CNP manager Brandi Ladnier has been assisted by Carol Odom, Vicky Malone, Credea Dixon, Joann Nelson of Theodore, Toni Broughton of Denton and volunteer Kathy Sullivan. On Tuesday, the menu included deli sandwiches, carrots, fruit, milk and juice. "It's great to be able to feed the children," Ladnier said. "I know there are a lot of children that without the school feeding them they wouldn't have anything." The children have been appreciative, as well, as a wall in Hankins' cafeteria is filled with their handmade cards and messages of thanks. We thank them as well! #IamMCPSS

post_text: FEEDING OUR CHILDREN: The cafeteria at Grand Bay Middle School has been operating with the help of cafeteria managers and workers from several other south Mobile County schools. Kay Cook has overseen the cafeteria, with help from Tammy James, Shani Clark, Julie Smith and Fran Kinn. On Friday, they handed out 936 bagged meals with breakfast and lunch, including turkey sandwiches, fruit roll-ups, fruit cups, juice and milk. "I feel blessed I can still work and I can still serve the community and the families in the area by providing lunch and breakfast for their children," said Smith, who is from Anna Booth Elementary. Thanks to all all these ladies for feeding our children! #IamMCPSS

post_text: We would like to thank Austal and its employees for a $15,000 donation to Mobile County Public Schools to assist with our feeding program and our televised learning. Our cafeterias are serving a total of 300,000 meals weekly at 66 sites throughout the county. Thank you, Austal, for supporting us as we support our children!

post_text: Today, which is School Lunch Hero Day, we salute our cafeteria workers. They have been busy serving meals curbside daily (for a total of 300,000/week) throughout this pandemic to make sure no child goes hungry. We have been featuring them in our FEEDING OUR CHILDREN series here on Facebook and will continue to do so. Pictured here are the staff and volunteers at Whitley Elementary, which has also been serving Mobile County Training School. "We have a lot of kids who look forward to these meals every day," said cafeteria manager Charita Terrell. "This has been such a blessing to our community." Others working at the Whitley site include: Patricia Thomas, Lavale Mose, Kiwania Daniels, Marilyn Bethel, Principal JaaDaa Holcombe and MCPSS Executive Manager of Information Technology David K. Akridge. During our visit, the staff was preparing corn dogs and potato wedges. So far, the favorite meal has been cheeseburgers. #LearningLeading #IamMCPSS #TeamMCPSS

post_text: FEEDING OUR CHILDREN: A little rain didn't stop the cafeteria workers and volunteers at Baker High School from handing out 728 meals featuring the ever-popular chili crispitos on Wednesday. The rain did keep the numbers down a bit as Baker, which also sends a bus with meals to Causey and Collier, often serves over 1,000 meals in a day. The Baker site is operated by cafeteria manager Veronica Tribbitt, cafeteria workers Sharon Jackson, Liz Mitchell and Johvita Turner, Central Office volunteers Paula Reese and Treba Young, and a couple of helpers from other schools: Debra Ferguson from Burns and Samantha Nettles from Anna Booth. "The first truck that was here this morning, that's one of our students and he calls me 'Mom.' He comes faithfully every morning to get his breakfast and lunch," Ms. Tribbitt said. "I am happy to see them, love them to death." Thank you to Ms. Tribbitt and the whole crew at Baker for all you do! #IamMCPSS

post_text: What does a chili crispito have to do with math? We had a great day of middle and high school reading and math today on mcpssTV's LIVE Lessons. Props included chili crispitos to illustrate random sampling and statistical inferencing; cones and cylinders to show the differences in measuring volume; and even a heavy homemade barbell lifted by our Geometry teacher. If you missed the lessons, you can catch them on our Facebook page or on mcpssTV's YouTube channel. #LearningLeading

post_text: FEEDING OUR CHILDREN: Holloway Elementary cafeteria manager Deborah Adams and her team handed out 849 bagged meals with ham sandwiches, muffins, broccoli, cauliflower, fruit and juice on Tuesday. Ms. Adams operates the cafeteria with help from her team of John Morgan, Kenya Hale, Kinondra Goldsmith and LaQuinta Freeman and volunteer Monique Baugh, the principal of Just 4 Developmental Laboratory. Holloway Principal Metra Turner and teacher Nancy Gardner were also on hand Tuesday, accepting completed academic packets from parents. "It truly has been a joy for me to be able to serve our children, to make sure they have a nutritious lunch and breakfast," Ms. Adams said. Thank you to her entire team for all they do! #IamMCPSS

post_text: FEEDING OUR CHILDREN: Today, cafeteria workers and volunteers at Vigor High School served 837 bagged lunches featuring pizza pockets and corn dogs with milk, juice, cereal, pop tarts, apples, oranges, applesauce and raisins. The Vigor site is operated by cafeteria manager Alma North and her team of Nonya Jones, Regina Marshall, Yolanda Payton and Gellie Roberts, with help from Wolfpack coaches TeBiarus Gill and Rashad Johnson. "It's been an adventure," North says. "We have kids who come up here and say sweet words to us. Their parents tell us how grateful they are. We're grateful to have them. ... It makes me feel good. The only thing I'm sorry I can't do is grab some of them and hug them." Thank you to Ms. North and her whole team! #IamMCPSS

post_text:
The Mobile County Board of School Commissioners will meet on Monday, April 27, 2020, for its monthly work session at 10 a.m. and for its monthly meeting at 10:30 a.m. Both meetings will be held in the Board Room at the MCPSS Central Office, located at 1 Magnum Pass in west Mobile. The board will take action on contracts, personnel items and other matters. The agenda is available here: https://simbli.eboardsolutions.com/SB_Meetings/ViewMeeting.aspx?S=2077&MID=12239

Pursuant to the Governor’s First Supplemental Order dated March 18, 2020, the Alabama Department of Public Health’s Order dated April 3, 2020, and in the interests of public health and safety, only board member and essential board employees will be permitted into the meeting room. The public will be able to view the meeting LIVE on the mcpssTV Facebook page. A summary of the actions taken will be posted to the system’s website within 12 hours of the end of the meeting.

post_text:
Due to the potential threat of bad weather throughout the county tomorrow, I have made the decision to cancel all feeding programs to include the preparation sites in our cafeterias as well as the delivery sites on Thursday, April 23. This decision was made to ensure the safety of all involved in the feeding program, including our workers, volunteers, parents and students. We will resume our normal hours for serving meals on Friday, April 24.

Thank you, and have a great evening.
Chresal D. Threadgill
Superintendent
Mobile County Public Schools

Thank you to the interpreters and mcpssTV film crew, too. #LearningLeading #IamMCPSS

post_text: FEEDING OUR CHILDREN: Today we are spotlighting the cafeteria managers, workers, bus drivers and volunteers who have been serving free lunches at Old Shell Road Magnet School. Today, under the leadership of Patricia Brown, they prepared about 270 sausage dogs and packaged them with chips, carrots, string cheese, fruit cups, apples, fruit juice and milk to serve curbside at Old Shell Road by bus delivery to Phillips Preparatory and Mary B. Austin Elementary. "The parents are so grateful that they are able to get these lunches for their children," Brown said. "They tell us that this is helping them a lot." Brown said she appreciates her cafeteria workers, Mary B. Austin Cafeteria Manager Denise Williams, and volunteers including a teacher and workers in the school's after-school program, who have been helping prepare the meals. So far, the most popular menu items at OSR have been grilled chicken sandwiches and chicken salad croissants. Please join us in saying THANK YOU! #IamMCPSS #LearningLeading

post_text:
Parents of students who applied for Pre-K at these 10 sites should receive an email within the mext week regarding whether your child has been accepted or waitlisted:
- Allentown
- Collier
- Gilliard
- Hutchens
- St. Elmo
- Castlen
- Dodge
- Howard
- McDavid-Jones
- J.E. Turner
The selection criteria at our other sites is different and requires screenings, which have been delayed due to COVID-19 precautions until clearance has been given for all employees to return to work with campus access. Parents will be notified of screening dates and locations once they are available. You will receive email notification regarding the delayed screening and pertinent updates as they become available.
